summary:
The Security Council adopted Resolution 2424 (2018) on June 29, 2018, recalling previous resolutions and statements on the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC). The Council reaffirmed its commitment to the DRC's sovereignty, independence, unity, and territorial integrity. 

The Council took note of the final report of the Group of Experts on the DRC and reiterated the need for the Government of the DRC to investigate the killing of two members of the Group of Experts and four accompanying Congolese nationals, and bring those responsible to justice.

The Council determined that the situation in the DRC continues to threaten international peace and security in the region and, acting under Chapter VII of the Charter, decided to:

1. Renew until July 1, 2019, the measures set out in paragraphs 1 to 6 of Resolution 2293 (2016);
2. Reaffirm that measures shall apply to individuals and entities designated by the Committee;
3. Extend until August 1, 2019, the mandate of the Group of Experts and requests the Secretary-General to re-establish the Group;
4. Request the Group of Experts to provide a mid-term report by December 30, 2018, and a final report by June 15, 2019, and submit monthly updates to the Committee;
5. Reaffirm reporting provisions set out in Resolution 2360 (2017);
6. Remain seized of the matter.
